WEBVTT

00:00.044 --> 00:01.297
<i>Previously on "Suits"...</i>

00:01.321 --> 00:02.570
<i>I don't owe Harvey shit.</i>

00:02.576 --> 00:03.520
He may have gotten me out,

00:03.521 --> 00:05.157
but he done came and put me
in there in the first place.

00:05.257 --> 00:06.473
You're right,
you don't owe Harvey,

00:06.508 --> 00:08.224
but you do owe me
because I didn't have anything

00:08.324 --> 00:09.423
to do with putting you in there,

00:09.458 --> 00:11.909
but I broke the law
to get you out.

00:11.961 --> 00:14.678
I came here to compliment you
on getting rid of Sheila's ass.

00:14.713 --> 00:17.047
If she's not back
by the start of trial,

00:17.099 --> 00:19.433
I'm gonna assume you want
to be brought up on charges.

00:19.435 --> 00:21.318
I just stopped by to give you
this restraining order

00:21.353 --> 00:23.370
preventing you
from contacting Louis Litt.

00:23.405 --> 00:25.656
You're done driving a wedge
between me and my people.

00:25.708 --> 00:27.875
If I represent myself,
every second I'm up there

00:27.927 --> 00:29.209
they're gonna see me
as a lawyer.

00:29.211 --> 00:30.344
And if she rattles you

00:30.379 --> 00:31.979
for one of those
goddamn seconds,

00:32.014 --> 00:33.347
they're gonna see you as a fraud

00:33.349 --> 00:35.215
and they're never gonna see you
as anything else.

00:35.251 --> 00:39.086
Did Mike Ross go
to Harvard Law School or not?

00:39.121 --> 00:42.122
I'd like to assert
my Fifth Amendment right.

00:42.124 --> 00:44.258
If I was on that jury,
I'd find you guilty.

00:44.293 --> 00:46.009
They're not gonna
let me change my goddamn lawyer

00:46.061 --> 00:47.394
in the middle of a trial.

00:47.429 --> 00:48.862
We need to figure out
a way to make them,

00:48.898 --> 00:50.864
'cause if we don't,
we're gonna lose.

00:50.900 --> 00:53.467
You have one last chance
to save yourself.

00:53.502 --> 00:56.286
Call me before it's too late.

01:00.252 --> 01:02.269
Okay, so we have
a plan for you

01:02.321 --> 01:03.654
to start representing yourself.

01:03.689 --> 01:06.156
We just need a way to rattle
Gibbs when we execute it.

01:06.208 --> 01:07.958
I have a way, but...

01:07.993 --> 01:11.178
you're not gonna like it.

01:11.213 --> 01:12.829
I'm gonna call Clifford Danner
to the stand.

01:12.865 --> 01:14.298
No way, it's too risky.

01:14.333 --> 01:16.600
- Harvey, listen to me--
- He's angry and volatile

01:16.652 --> 01:17.834
and in case you forgot,

01:17.870 --> 01:19.336
he's one of the people
you were dumb enough

01:19.371 --> 01:21.238
to tell your secret to.
I know all of that,

01:21.273 --> 01:23.373
but you said it yourself,
we need sympathy,

01:23.375 --> 01:25.125
and no one is gonna
get us more sympathy

01:25.177 --> 01:27.311
than the innocent guy
we got out of prison.

01:27.346 --> 01:29.513
Harvey, you said
I needed to do this.

01:29.515 --> 01:31.815
Well, this is how I do it.

01:31.867 --> 01:33.450
<i>[tense music]</i>

01:33.485 --> 01:35.569
Do you have faith in me or not?

01:35.621 --> 01:42.426
<i>♪
♪</i>

01:42.478 --> 01:43.560
[door opens]

01:44.863 --> 01:46.363
Mrs. Gloria Danner?

01:46.398 --> 01:48.615
- Yes.
- Hi, my name is Mike Ross.

01:48.667 --> 01:50.867
I'm a lawyer at Pearson Specter
Litt and I was hoping--

01:50.903 --> 01:52.302
I know who you are,

01:52.338 --> 01:54.471
and I know
what you're doing here.

01:54.506 --> 01:57.858
You've come to get Clifford
to testify for you,

01:57.893 --> 01:59.826
but I'm afraid
he's not going to.

01:59.862 --> 02:02.529
Please, ma'am, I promise you,
the DA cannot reopen his case--

02:02.581 --> 02:05.999
I'm not talking
about the district attorney.

02:06.051 --> 02:08.935
My son's dead, Mr. Ross.

02:08.971 --> 02:10.604
<i>♪
♪</i>

02:11.197 --> 02:13.214
- What?
- Clifford was shot and killed

02:13.249 --> 02:16.000
three weeks ago, so...

02:16.052 --> 02:18.386
I'm sorry, he can't help you.

02:18.421 --> 02:20.555
<i>♪
♪</i>

02:20.607 --> 02:22.139
<i>- Hello?</i>
- Are you in the office?

02:22.191 --> 02:24.158
<i>It's Thursday night.</i>
<i>I'm watching my show.</i>

02:24.193 --> 02:26.377
<i>Well, then goddamn Tivo it</i>
<i>because I need your help.</i>

02:26.412 --> 02:29.080
It better be important if
you're taking that tone with me.

02:29.132 --> 02:31.098
And if this is
about that mah-jongg game--

02:31.134 --> 02:32.466
I don't give a shit
if it's mah-jongg

02:32.518 --> 02:34.402
or kung pao or Chinese checkers.

02:34.437 --> 02:35.820
This is the most important thing

02:35.855 --> 02:38.239
that I'm ever gonna ask you
to do in your entire life.

02:39.049 --> 02:40.421
Give me an order.

02:40.422 --> 02:42.088
<i>I need you to pull</i>
<i>whatever strings you have</i>

02:42.090 --> 02:43.606
to get me a transcript
of Mike's trial

02:43.642 --> 02:45.141
and I need you
to keep it to yourself.

02:45.193 --> 02:46.659
Mind if I ask
what you need it for?

02:46.695 --> 02:48.945
Because I need to know if we
have a snowball's chance in hell

02:48.997 --> 02:50.697
of winning this thing.

02:50.699 --> 02:53.333
Is defense ready
to call its first witness?

02:53.385 --> 02:55.168
- I am, Your Honor.
- What?

02:55.170 --> 02:56.302
I'm calling my witness.

02:56.304 --> 02:58.555
Does prosecution have a problem
with that?

02:58.607 --> 03:00.640
Objection, this is outrageous,
Your Honor.

03:00.675 --> 03:02.525
They can't switch attorneys
in the middle of a trial.

03:02.577 --> 03:04.110
And that would be true
except for the fact

03:04.162 --> 03:06.279
that I've been co-counsel
on this case from day one.

03:06.331 --> 03:08.114
Co-counsel?
What planer are you living on?

03:08.150 --> 03:10.717
The one where Pearson Specter
Litt is my attorney of record.

03:10.719 --> 03:12.519
I have the employee directory
right here.

03:12.554 --> 03:13.853
My name is in it.
It's been there

03:13.855 --> 03:15.188
since the beginning
of this trial,

03:15.190 --> 03:16.439
and if you wanted
to object to me,

03:16.491 --> 03:17.574
you would have had
to have done it

03:17.609 --> 03:19.092
at the beginning of this trial.

03:19.127 --> 03:20.827
Then I want them waiving
all rights to a mistrial

03:20.829 --> 03:22.295
and I want it in the record.
Your Honor,

03:22.297 --> 03:24.130
I'm not gonna be punished just
because she didn't understand

03:24.132 --> 03:26.590
that I've been representing
myself this whole time.

03:26.690 --> 03:27.856
He's got a point, Ms. Gibbs.

03:27.908 --> 03:29.991
Then I want them waiving
all rights to a mistrial

03:30.027 --> 03:31.860
based on
him representing himself.

03:31.862 --> 03:33.328
My pleasure, Your Honor,
'cause I don't expect

03:33.330 --> 03:34.963
we'll be needing a mistrial
at all.

03:34.998 --> 03:36.381
Then call your first witness.

03:36.416 --> 03:40.135
Defense would like to call
Gloria Danner to the stand.

03:40.137 --> 03:41.803
<i>Please state your name</i>
<i>for the jury.</i>

03:41.805 --> 03:43.938
Gloria Danner.

03:43.974 --> 03:45.774
Mrs. Danner,

03:45.809 --> 03:47.609
a number of years ago,
your son Clifford

03:47.611 --> 03:50.245
was convicted of murder
and sentenced to prison,

03:50.280 --> 03:52.113
is that right?
Yes.

03:52.115 --> 03:53.715
For a crime he didn't commit.

03:53.750 --> 03:55.083
How do you know
he didn't commit it

03:55.085 --> 03:56.334
if he was convicted of it?

03:56.386 --> 03:58.420
Because you proved he didn't.

03:58.472 --> 04:00.088
Mrs. Danner,
can you tell the jury

04:00.140 --> 04:02.223
why it is that you're here today
testifying

04:02.259 --> 04:03.725
and not your son Clifford?

04:03.777 --> 04:05.727
He was working late
at the diner.

04:05.779 --> 04:09.397
It was the only place he could
get a job when he got out.

04:09.449 --> 04:11.900
Two men came in
to rob the place,

04:11.902 --> 04:13.968
and when Clifford tried
to stop them,

04:14.004 --> 04:17.204
he was shot and killed.

04:17.257 --> 04:19.974
<i>[somber music]</i>

04:20.010 --> 04:22.177
I'm so sorry.

04:22.179 --> 04:26.681
[crying]
I worked my whole life

04:26.733 --> 04:28.450
to put him through school

04:28.485 --> 04:30.985
and he ends up dying

04:30.987 --> 04:33.872
in the back of that
shit restaurant

04:33.907 --> 04:36.658
in that shit part of town.

04:36.693 --> 04:38.626
Can you tell the jury
why you agreed

04:38.628 --> 04:41.129
to come share your story
for me today?

04:41.181 --> 04:42.964
<i>♪
♪</i>

04:42.966 --> 04:44.766
Prison

04:44.801 --> 04:47.435
ruined Clifford's life...

04:47.487 --> 04:48.853
<i>♪
♪</i>

04:48.905 --> 04:51.356
And if you had been our lawyer

04:51.408 --> 04:53.191
from day one,

04:53.243 --> 04:56.411
he never would have been
convicted in the first place.

04:56.413 --> 04:59.798
<i>♪
♪</i>

04:59.833 --> 05:01.616
Thank you, Gloria.

05:01.651 --> 05:03.802
<i>♪
♪</i>

05:03.854 --> 05:06.387
No more questions, Your Honor.

05:06.389 --> 05:11.643
<i>♪
♪</i>

05:11.695 --> 05:13.445
Mrs. Danner,

05:13.480 --> 05:17.398
I happen to be familiar
with your son's case.

05:17.451 --> 05:19.901
and I understand
that in order to reopen it,

05:19.953 --> 05:23.788
Mr. Ross risked
increasing his sentence to life.

05:23.824 --> 05:25.039
That's correct.

05:25.075 --> 05:26.908
Well, I'd like to know
how you'd have felt

05:26.910 --> 05:28.326
if he lost that gamble.

05:28.378 --> 05:29.744
I'd have been devastated.

05:29.796 --> 05:31.830
And if that happened,
how would you have felt

05:31.882 --> 05:33.081
if you then found out that

05:33.133 --> 05:36.084
Mr. Ross wasn't even a lawyer
after all?

05:36.086 --> 05:38.553
Objection, Your Honor, how
many hypotheticals can she ask?

05:38.588 --> 05:39.754
That's okay.

05:39.756 --> 05:42.590
I think everybody
in this courtroom knows

05:42.642 --> 05:45.760
how they would feel.

05:45.812 --> 05:48.763
No more questions, Your Honor.

05:48.765 --> 05:52.267
I wouldn't have cared what
a piece of paper had to say,

05:52.319 --> 05:56.271
because Mr. Ross is
the only lawyer I ever ran into

05:56.273 --> 05:59.107
that ever gave a damn
about my son.

05:59.109 --> 06:02.660
<i>♪
♪</i>

06:02.696 --> 06:05.830
Mr. Ross, would you care
to call your next witness?

06:05.866 --> 06:09.701
<i>♪
♪</i>

06:09.753 --> 06:10.869
I can't imagine anyone

06:10.921 --> 06:13.037
being more eloquent than that,
Your Honor.

06:13.089 --> 06:14.539
<i>♪
♪</i>

06:14.591 --> 06:18.510
Defense rests.

06:19.045 --> 06:22.713
<i>♪ See the money,</i>
<i>wanna stay for your meal ♪</i>

06:22.765 --> 06:26.050
<i>♪ Get another piece of pie</i>
<i>for your wife ♪</i>

06:26.102 --> 06:29.220
<i>♪ Everybody wanna know</i>
<i>how it feel ♪</i>

06:29.272 --> 06:32.973
<i>♪ Everybody wanna see</i>
<i>what it's like ♪</i>

06:33.026 --> 06:35.893
<i>♪ I'll even eat a bean pie,</i>
<i>I don't mind ♪</i>

06:35.945 --> 06:39.897
<i>♪ Me and Missy is</i>
<i>so busy, busy making money ♪</i>

06:39.949 --> 06:41.365
<i>♪ All right ♪</i>

06:41.401 --> 06:42.954
<i>♪ All step back,</i>
<i>I'm 'bout to dance ♪</i>

06:42.955 --> 06:46.955
<font color=#00FF00>♪ Suits 5x15 ♪</font>
<font color=#00FFFF>Tick Tock</font>
